<div class="not-prose mb-6 flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3 text-sm"><a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔍</span> Solver</a> <a href="/activities/#quiz" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🎯</span> Quiz</a> <a href="/activities/#anagram" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔀</span> Anagram</a> <a href="/activities/#rack" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🎲</span> Rack</a> <a href="/activities/#wotd" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">📖</span> WOTD</a> <a href="/sixty-seconds/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">⏱️</span> 60s</a></div>
<h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-2 leading-tight">Words Starting With PRE-</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8 not-prose">Quiz · Dictionary</p>

    <!-- Additional content for depth -->
    <div class="mt-10 border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 pt-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">Why PRE- Dominates Mid-Game</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">PRE- excels in mid-game because it transforms existing board words into longer plays. When opponents lay down HEAT, VIEW, or JUDGE, you can prepend PRE- in front for an instant extension that scores big.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">The P tile's 3-point value gives PRE- a natural scoring advantage over cheaper prefixes like RE- (2 pts) or UN- (2 pts). Every PRE- word starts with 5 guaranteed points before you even count the root word.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">PRE- also pairs beautifully with high-value roots. PREQUIZ uses the Q and Z together for a devastating 23-point play. PREFIXED deploys the X tile for 19 points. Always look for power-tile roots when holding P-R-E.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">For bingo hunters, PRE- is a 3-letter prefix that leaves 4 slots for root tiles. This sweet spot means you need a common 4-letter root for a bingo: PRE+VIEW, PRE+VENT, PRE+PARE, PRE+SENT — all familiar words that score 50+ bonus points.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">Finally, PRE- works as a defensive tool. By extending a word with PRE-, you often block premium squares from opponents while scoring substantial points yourself. It's both sword and shield in competitive play.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">Study these common PRE- roots for quick recall: HEAT, WASH, PAID, VIEW, VENT, SENT, PARE, TEND, FIX, JUDGE. Each creates a valid 7-8 letter word that most players recognise, reducing challenge risk.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">In late-game situations, short PRE- words like PREP (8pts), PREY (9pts), and PREX (13pts) become valuable because they deploy the P tile productively without committing to a long play on a crowded board.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">Remember that PREX (13 points) is one of the highest-scoring 4-letter PRE- words thanks to X(8). It's valid in SOWPODS and makes an excellent tight-board play when space is limited.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">For competitive players, the PRE- prefix appears in many "bingo stem" lists. Tournament preparation should include memorising the top 20 PRE- bingos for rapid board scanning during timed play.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">PRE- also works well in combination plays. You can prepend PRE- to a word and simultaneously add a suffix: HEAT → PREHEATED, PAY → PREPAYING. These compound extensions score enormous points by using 8-9 tiles.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Track the P tiles carefully — only 2 exist in the bag. Once both P tiles are played, PRE- opportunities end. Knowing the tile distribution helps you plan your prefix strategy across the full game.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Finally, PREY (9 points) and PREP (8 points) are excellent fallback plays when you hold P-R-E but can't find a longer word. They score well for their length and clear your rack for better draws next turn.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Combining PRE- with suffixes creates powerful compound plays: PREHEATED, PREPAYING, PREVIEWING. These 9-10 letter words score enormously when they cross premium squares — look for board openings that support long horizontal or vertical plays.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">For casual players, just memorise these 5 PRE- bingos: PREVIEW, PREVENT, PREPARE, PRESUME, PRESENT. These common English words cover most game situations and rarely get challenged.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Advanced tip: if an opponent plays JUDGE, immediately check if the left edge has space for PRE-. PREJUDGE is a valid 8-letter extension that scores big and demonstrates strong Scrabble vocabulary knowledge.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Summary: PRE- delivers a 5-point base, 400+ valid words, solid bingo potential, and clean attachment to hundreds of common English verbs. Add it to your prefix arsenal for consistent mid-game scoring.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Keep this mental checklist when holding P-R-E: check board for verbs to extend, check for premium square alignment, check if any 4-letter root creates a bingo. If none works, fall back to PREP/PREY/PREX as compact scoring plays.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">PRE- pairs especially well with -ED and -ING suffixes to create long compound plays. PREHEATED (10 letters), PREVIEWING (10 letters), PRETENDING (10 letters) — each crosses multiple premium squares for devastating scores.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">Start practising: in your next 5 games, actively look for PRE- opportunities. Track how often P-R-E appears on your rack and how many times you successfully deploy it. Most players find 2-3 PRE- plays per game once they start looking.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">The PRE- prefix rewards preparation — both in vocabulary knowledge and rack management. Master it and you'll have a reliable 5-point scoring foundation for the rest of your Scrabble career.</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mt-4">One last tip: PRE- words rarely get challenged in competitive play because they're familiar English. PREVIEW, PREPARE, PREVENT — opponents accept these without question, giving you stress-free scoring every time.</p>

    </div>

